<br>
Karadin Said:<br>
&quot;The RTA is an accomplishment, not because of some utopian nature wherein guilds forego the loot dropped from rare mobs out of some misformed charity complex – it is an accomplishment because it deals very realistically with the issues of sharing content and does so in a very fair and systematic way.&quot;<br>
<br>
Regarding Rotation mobs the RTA is pretty fair /agree However what your trying to do with the moral opinions is not fair.<br>
<br>
Karadin said:<br>
&quot;That is to say, what makes our community special, is not that we all stand back and watch 4+ small guilds try the Avatar of War until they beat him, but that we are able to share very limited resources that realistically factors in our collective greed. Abusing that system by teaming up to beat new content, but retaining separate guild status on other rotations should be a very obvious violation of the principles of that system.&quot;<br>
<br>
Again nobody is arguing rotation mobs regarding teaming/alliances its a rule, has been for a while. Yet the only tactical evidence you can provide as a detriment is the rotation mobs. We are not talking about rotation mobs so please stay on the issue Karadin.<br>
<br>
Karadin said:<br>
&quot;Your premise is weak, as it follows the unethical argument, that as long as everyone is allowed to exploit this, it isn’t a problem. Taking twice the loot out of old world rotations, but teaming solely for PoP mobs abuses the system and gives an advantage over those who don’t do the same.&quot;<br>
<br>
Again more with the mixing of rotation/non rotation mobs. And as far as teaming on pop mobs, which is the only issue here, does not provide advantage over those that can but don't have to do it. We are lucky, we have capable guilds, a good deal of the server population does not and that number is growing with pop being the only viable xp expansion for 60+. <br>
<br>
Karadin said:<br>
&quot;And yes, I do consider having morons in other zones with me as hurting my playtime and enjoyment&quot;<br>
<br>
